{"parentUuid":"68bc33b0-603d-4724-8c75-d9ecd390e831","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/douglaswross/Code/gofer","sessionId":"d5677db6-e08e-491d-8b1d-4ff8f868cb8f","version":"2.1.37","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a90504c","slug":"vast-wobbling-taco","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017XVW2q4P3jUis7J7BNJCEW","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→id: 022-memory-categorization-cleanup\n     3→title: Memory System Categorization Cleanup\n     4→status: draft\n     5→created: '2026-02-11'\n     6→updated: '2026-02-11'\n     7→author: Claude\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→# Memory System Categorization Cleanup\n    11→\n    12→## Overview\n    13→\n    14→The Gofer extension's sidebar panels have blurred boundaries. The Memory panel displays items that belong to other systems (observations, constitution access), the context budget system treats constitution as memory, and the layered memory system wraps constitution as a fake memory entry causing double-loading. This creates naming confusion for developers maintaining the code and a confusing UX for end users.\n    15→\n    16→**Target Users**: Developers maintaining the Gofer codebase and end users of the VSCode extension.\n    17→**Primary Value**: Each panel and system has a distinct, non-overlapping identity in both code and UI.\n    18→\n    19→**Discovery Reference**: See `discovery.md` for full business context.\n    20→**Research Reference**: See `research.md` for codebase analysis and integration points.\n    21→\n    22→## User Stories\n    23→\n    24→### US1: Memory Panel Shows Only Memories (P1)\n    25→\n    26→**As a** Gofer extension user\n    27→**I want** the Memory panel to show only learned knowledge (memories, decisions)\n    28→**So that** I have a clear mental model of what \"Memory\" means\n    29→\n    30→**Acceptance Criteria**:\n    31→\n    32→- [ ] The Memory panel no longer shows an \"Observations\" section\n    33→- [ ] The Memory panel no longer shows a \"Checkpoints\" section\n    34→- [ ] The Memory panel shows only: Memories (by category) and Decisions (ADRs)\n    35→- [ ] The Memory panel no longer has a \"Show Constitution\" toolbar button\n    36→\n    37→### US2: Constitution Is Independent from Memory (P1)\n    38→\n    39→**As a** developer maintaining the Gofer codebase\n    40→**I want** constitution to have its own identity separate from the memory system\n    41→**So that** I can reason about each system independently without confusion\n    42→\n    43→**Acceptance Criteria**:\n    44→\n    45→- [ ] Constitution has its own budget category in `ContextBuilder` (not lumped with memories)\n    46→- [ ] `MemoryLayerManager` no longer wraps constitution as a `MemoryItem`\n    47→- [ ] Constitution is loaded exactly once in context assembly (no double-loading)\n    48→- [ ] The `config.ts` VIEWS constant no longer references the removed `goferConstitution` view\n    49→\n    50→### US3: Context Window Owns Context-Related Concerns (P2)\n    51→\n    52→**As a** Gofer extension user\n    53→**I want** the Context Window panel to be the single source of truth for context health information\n    54→**So that** I know where to look for observation counts, token budgets, and session status\n    55→\n    56→**Acceptance Criteria**:\n    57→\n    58→- [ ] The Context Window panel's \"Memories/Hints\" category is renamed to accurately reflect what it shows\n    59→- [ ] Observation information is no longer duplicated between Memory and Context Window panels\n    60→\n    61→### US4: Configuration Constants Are Accurate (P2)\n    62→\n    63→**As a** developer maintaining the Gofer codebase\n    64→**I want** the `config.ts` constants to accurately reflect the current state of registered views\n    65→**So that** I can trust the codebase as documentation\n    66→\n    67→**Acceptance Criteria**:\n    68→\n    69→- [ ] `config.ts` VIEWS constant includes `contextWindow: 'goferContextWindow'`\n    70→- [ ] `config.ts` VIEWS constant removes the stale `constitution: 'goferConstitution'` entry\n    71→- [ ] No other stale view references exist in configuration\n    72→\n    73→## Functional Requirements\n    74→\n    75→### FR1: Remove Observations Section from Mem
